to adding much needed substance to our understanding of the history and politics of "culture," taken together confirm the practical advantages to the sort of rigorous and dynamic interdisciplinarity ever more a part of academic life. Concepts of Culture: Art, Politics, and Society also helps to secure a place for analytic philosophy, humanism, and liberal political theory in contemporary debates over what exactly "culture" is and how it works. Contributors include such distinguished scholars as Jacques Barzun, Geoffrey Hartman, Mette Hjort, and Martha Nussbaum. With Contributions By: Jacques Barzun Christoph Brumann Geoffrey Hartman Mette Hjort Rhonda Martens Carl Matheson Adam Muller David Novitz Martha Nussbaum Jim Parry Martin Roberts Robert Stecker Imre Szeman  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCulturevTextbooks. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aabstract culture.  aaesthetics and culture.  aart and culture.  abooks about culture.  aconcepts of culture.  acultural studies.  aculture and globalization.  afilm and culture.  afilm culture.  asport culture.  asports and culture.  astudy of culture.  auniversal values.1 aBarzun, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrumann, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartman, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHjort, Mette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartens, Rhonda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatheson, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuller, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuller, Adam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNov